## Plan

**Approach:** Add ONE new compact doc `docs/plans/dogfood/checklists.md` that is
the single operational index for the three high-frequency flows — Session Boot,
Gate Execution, Close. Each flow is a short numbered list where every active step
is either a COMMAND (already mechanized) or a one-line check, and each step links
to the runbook/capture-protocol/lens section that holds its rationale. The three
long docs (README, review-gate-runbook, capture-protocol) keep all their prose as
rationale/reference and gain a single 1-2 line pointer at the top sending the
operator to the relevant checklist for the active steps. The checklist REFERENCES
mechanisms and sections; it does NOT copy their content (copies drift). This is
the literal acceptance: "Session Boot, gate execution, and close protocol EACH
point to a short checklist or command."

**Form decision (+ rationale):** ONE new `checklists.md`, cross-linked from all
three docs — NOT in-place blocks. Rationale:
- The acceptance wants "the long runbook is no longer the ONLY operational
  source." A single checklists doc IS that second, compact operational source;
  in-place blocks would just re-thicken the same long docs the retro (§3) flagged
  as overloaded.
- The three flows span three different files (boot=README, gate=runbook,
  close=capture-protocol + dogfood-close.sh). A single index lets an operator
  open ONE page to run any flow instead of hunting three docs. After a context
  clear, Session Boot can say "open checklists.md" — one entry point.
- It keeps the no-duplication contract clean: the checklist is an INDEX of
  commands+links, and each rule still has exactly one authoritative home (the
  script, the make target, the runbook lens section, the capture-protocol
  section). The doc explicitly states "this page is an index; rationale lives at
  the linked section."
- Cost: one extra cross-link to maintain per doc. Mitigated by keeping the
  pointer to a single line and pointing each checklist STEP at a section anchor
  (drift shows up as a dead anchor, not silent wrongness).

